definition.value: Testing for the sexually transmitted disease gonorrhea.
Screening for hepatitis C antibodies to determine if a patient has immunity to hepatitis C.
Collecting of blood for clinical use.
Collecting of bile for clinical use.
A procedure to tell what a patient's blood type and cell surface markers are.
A procedured performed to determine the antigens patient's red blood cells (RBCs) that correspond to the four main blood groups: A, B, O, and AB.

Testing to determine whether the protien Rhesus (Rh) factor is present on patient's red blood cells. If the protein is present, the patient is said to be Rh positive. If the protein is not present, the patient is Rh negative.

value.value: A quantitative measurement of the amount of hemoglobin present in a sample.

definition.value: A determination of the number of reticulocyte in a blood sample.
A quantitative measurement of the amount of iron in serum.
A quantitative measurement determining the amount of ferritin in serum as an indicator of iron metabolism.

value.value: The determination of the saturation of iron binding sites on serum transferrin proteins.

definition.value: A measurement of size, shape, number, or other parameter of blood cells in order to diagnose or treat a patient.
A determination of the structure of erythrocyte.
A procedure taking a thin layer of blood smeared on a glass microscope slide and stained to allow blood cells to be examined with a microscope.

value.value: A quantitative measurement of the amount of creatinine present in a sample of serum.
Serves to assist in the evaluation of renal function.

definition.value: The determination of the amount of thyroid stimulating hormone present in blood.
Determination of thyroxine (T4) levels in the blood as an indicator of thyroid health.
Determination of triiodothyronine (T3) levels in blood as an indicator of thyroid health.
A measure of a patient's ability to clot, and how long it takes to clot.

A measurement of the length of time that it takes for clotting to occur when reagents are added to a plasma specimen. The test is partial due to the absence of tissue factor (Factor III) from the reaction mixture.

value.value: The determination of the ratio of the prothrombin time in a subject's specimen compared to a control sample. The measurement may be expressed as a ratio or percentage.
A measurement of the time it takes a plasma sample to clot after adding the active enzyme thrombin.

definition.value: The determination of the amount of alanine aminotransferase (human) present in the sample.

value.value: Alanine aminotransferase is an enzyme produced mainly in the liver. When serum activity is measured, it provides a marker of hepatic disease.

definition.value: The determination of the amount of aspartate aminotransferase (human) present in the sample.

value.value: Alanine aminotransferase (ALT), aspartate aminotransferase (AST) and gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT) are enzymes measured in serum or plasma to investigate liver disease.

definition.value: The determination of the amount of gamma-glutamyltranspeptidase present in the sample.

value.value: Determination of gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT) present in the sample as a measurement of liver function.

definition.value: The determination of the amount of albumin (human) present in the sample.
The determination of the amount of alkaline phosphatase present in the sample.

value.value: The measurement of the total amount of bilirubin present in a particular substrate. The substrate most often tested is blood, but other fluids extracted from the body may be used periodically depending on the purpose of the test.

definition.value: The determination of the amount of lactate dehydrogenase present in the sample.
The determination of the amount of 5'-nucleotidase present in the sample.
The measurement of bilirubin present in a particular sample.
A measurement of the unconjugated or non-water-soluble bilirubin in a biological specimen.
A quantitative measurement of total protein present in the sample, usually serum or urine.
The determination of the amount of protein present in urine.

value.value: The measurement of the total protein present in a urine sample that was collected over a period of 24 hours.
A quantitative measurement of the total amount of protein present in a sample of serum.

definition.value: The determination of the amount of haptoglobin present in the sample.
Determination of the types of normal or abnormal types of hemoglobin in the blood. Some types of hemoglobin are associated with sickle cell disease or anemia.

Determination of serum levels of pregnancy-associated plasma protein A (PAPP-A). Maternal levels of PAPP-A increase throughout the pregnancy. Low levels during pregnancy are associated with Down syndrome and trisomy 18.

value.value: A test that involves administration of a know quantity of glucose as a means of screening for glucose intolerance or diabetes mellitus. Typically a baseline (fasting plasma or serum glucose) is drawn prior to the administration of the glucose bolus.  Serial plasma glucose levels are obtained (e.g. 30min, 1hr, 2hr, 3hr) and a plot of plasma glucose versus time is created.  Comparison of these values against standardized results can be used in establishing the diagnosis of glucose intolerance or diabetes mellitus.
A test or diagnostic examination to assess the health status and well being of the fetus.
A series of maneuvers to determine the position and presenting part of the fetus with respect to the maternal pelvic canal in preparation for labor and the birth process.

The use of pharmacological and/or mechanical methods to initiate labor, including spontaneous rupture of membranes without contractions. Examples of methods include: artificial rupture of membranes, balloons, oxytocin, prostaglandin, laminaria, or other cervical ripening agents. (adapted from reVITALize)
A method to assess fetal oxygenation status during labor and delivery using a noninvasive reflectance pulse oximeter.

definition.value: The determination of the amount of protein present in blood.
A systemic evaluation of the abdomen using visual inspection, palpation, and percussion during pregnancy to determine the health of the mother and fetus.
A quantitative measurement of the amount of human chorionic gonadotropin present in urine or serum for the purpose of determining whether the patient is pregnant.
A systemic evaluation of the cervix during pregnancy to determine dilation and effacement of the cervix, cervical position and consistancy, and fetal position.
An evaluation of the breast using visual inspection, palpation, and percussion for the specific purpose of identifying breast changes which may be cancer.
